> Raise your hand if you're obsessed with anything involving gnocchi. If you're new to
> gnocchi, it's a pasta/dumpling hybrid that's made with potatoes, resulting in
> an extra-tender, extra-carby bite. Here, it's paired with spinach and grape
> tomatoes, then tossed in a creamy sauce. To top things off—in this case literally—
> there's a layer of garlicky panko breadcrumbs. It's the perfect crispy contrast
> to this rich dish. Once you take a bite, don't be surprised when you find yourself
> making excuses to whip it up again and again!

Bring a #medium pot{} of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry all produce.

Halve @Grape Tomatoes{4%ounce}. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @Shallot{1}.

Melt @Butter{1%tbsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @Panko Breadcrumbs{¼%cup}; cook, stirring, until golden and toasted, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in half the @Garlic Powder{1%teaspoon} (you'll use the rest later) and cook until just fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Wipe out pan.

Once water is boiling, add @Gnocchi{8.8%ounce} to #pot{}. Cook until tender, ~{3-4%minutes}. Drain.

While gnocchi cooks, melt @Butter{1%tbsp} in pan used for panko over medium-high heat. Add shallot and cook until slightly softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in remaining garlic powder and cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in @water{⅓%cup}, @Veggie Stock Concentrate{1} and @Cream Cheese{4%tablespoon}. Bring to a simmer, stirring, until combined and creamy, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Stir tomatoes and @Baby Spinach{5%ounce} into pan with sauce. Cook, stirring, until spinach is wilted and tomatoes are softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir drained gnocchi into pan with sauce until thoroughly coated, adding water a splash or two at a time as needed. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Divide gnocchi between #bowls{} and top with @Parmesan Cheese{¼%cup}. Sprinkle with as much garlic panko as you like. Add a pinch of @Chili Flakes{1%teaspoon} to taste and serve.